{{Infobox person | name = Jean-Christophe Victor | image = Jean-Christophe Victor 2013.jpg | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date|df=y|1947|05|30}} | birth_place = [[Paris]], France | death_date = {{death date and age|2016|12|28|1947|05|30|df=yes}} | death_place = [[Montpellier]], France | death_cause = [[Myocardial infarction|Heart attack]] | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = | residence = | nationality = [[France|French]] | other_names = | known_for = | education = | employer = | occupation = [[Political scientist]], [[ethnologist]], [[television host]] | title = | salary = | networth = | height = | weight = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | boards = | religion = | spouse = | partner = | children = | parents = [[Paul-Émile Victor]] | relatives = | signature = | website = | footnotes = }} '''Jean-Christophe Victor''' (30 May 1947 – 28 December 2016) was a [[political scientist]] focusing on [[international relations]]. He was the son of the polar explorer [[Paul-Emile Victor]] and the television producer [[Éliane Decrais]]. He earned a [[master's degree|Master]] in [[Chinese language]], a Master in [[political science]]s (1982) and a PhD in [[ethnology]] on [[Nepal]]. He was posted as a diplomat in [[Afghanistan]], worked as policy adviser at [[Nato]]- Bruxelles, and for the Policy Planning Office at the [[French Ministry of Foreign Affairs]].
He was the founder and the director of [[LEPAC]], the Center for Political Studies and Cartographic Analysis, a Paris-based "think tank". The LEPAC trains international managers in the corporate sector for companies such as [[Veolia]], [[Vinci (construction)|Vinci]], [[Areva]], [[British Petroleum]], [[Cartier S.A.|Cartier]], and [[L’Oréal]]; and public sector organisations including [[RATP Group|RATP]], [[Council of Europe]], and the [[European Union]].
Victor taught [[geopolitics]] in [[France]] and in several foreign universities. The last books he authored on geopolitics are:
* "Le dessous des cartes : Itinéraires géopolitiques" (Beneath the Maps: Geopolitical Routes) 2011, Paris * "Political Atlas for Teenagers" 2010 ; Paris * "Atlas for a Changing World" 2008, Paris, Berlin, Seoul, Tokyo, Taipei.
He was the author of a weekly program on European channel [[Arte|ARTE]] and French world channel TV 5, dealing about geopolitics: "[[Le dessous des cartes]]" ("Underneath the Maps").<ref>{{cite news |title=Beau joueur, Jean-Christophe Victor |url=http://www.leparisien.fr/loisirs-et-spectacles/beau-joueur-jean-christophe-victor-20-10-2005-2006397773.php |work=[[le Parisien]] |date=20 October 2005 |accessdate=29 July 2010 }}</ref>
Jean-Christophe Victor died on 28 December 2016 due to a [[heart attack]].
== Bibliography == * ''Itinéraires géopolitiques, Atlas du dessous des cartes'', 2011, Editions Tallandier/Arte Editions * ''Le dessous des cartes - Atlas Junior'', 2010, (avec [[Dominique Fouchard]] et [[Catherine Barichnikoff]]), Editions Tallandier * 2007, (avec [[Paul-Emile Victor]])''Adieu l'Antarctique'', [[Laffont]], Paris * 2007, (avec [[:fr:Virginie Raisson|Virginie Raisson]] et [[Frank Tétart]]) ''Le dessous des cartes - Atlas d'un monde qui change'', Editions Tallandier * 2005, (avec [[Virginie Raisson]] et [[Frank Tétart]]) ''Le dessous des cartes - Atlas géopolitique'', Editions Tallandier * 1993, ''L'enjeu afghan ou La cité des murmures'', Editions Lattès, Paris * 1992, ''Planète Antarctique'' (avec [[Paul-Émile Victor]]), [[Laffont]], Paris * 1985, ''Armes : France Troisième Grand'', [[éditions Autrement]], Paris
