{{About|the crater on Mars|the lunar crater|Sklodowska (lunar crater)}}
'''Sklodowska''' is a [[Impact crater|crater]] on [[Mars]], located in the [[Mare Acidalium quadrangle]] at 33.7°N and 2.9°W. It measures {{convert|109.72 |km |mi |sigfig=3}} in diameter and was named after Polish chemist and first female Nobel Laureate [[Marie Skłodowska Curie]] (1867–1934). The naming was approved in 1973, by the International Astronomical Union's [[Working Group for Planetary System Nomenclature]].<ref name="Gazetteer-Sklodowska" />
== Gallery ==
Pictures of Sklodowska show numerous branched channels along its rim. Some are visible in the pictures below.
<gallery class="center" widths="190px" heights="180px" > Wikisklodowskamola.jpg|MOLA map showing Sklodowska Crater and other nearby craters. Color indicates elevation. Wikisklodowska.jpg|Sklodowska Crater, as seen by CTX camera (on [[Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter]]). Small channels are visible along the eroded, southern rim. Wikisklodowskachannels.jpg|Channels in Sklodowska Crater, as seen by CTX camera (on Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter). Note: this is an enlargement of the previous image. WikisklodowskaESP 035500 2130.jpg|Channels in Sklodowska Crater, as seen by HiRISE under the HiWish program. </gallery>
